&lt;h1 id="heresy"&gt;Heresy&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;April 2022&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;One of the most surprising things I&amp;rsquo;ve witnessed in my lifetime is the rebirth of the concept of heresy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In his excellent biography of Newton, Richard Westfall writes about the moment when he was elected a fellow of Trinity College: &amp;ldquo;Supported comfortably, Newton was free to devote himself wholly to whatever he chose. To remain on, he had only to avoid the three unforgivable sins: crime, heresy, and marriage.&amp;rdquo; [1] The first time I read that, in the 1990s, it sounded amusingly medieval. How strange, to have to avoid committing heresy. But when I reread it 20 years later it sounded like a description of contemporary employment.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>